  "notes": [
    {
      "title": "Doubled Verbs (الفعل المضعف)",
      "titleArabic": "الفعل المضعف",
      "content": [
        "Doubled verbs (الفعل المضعف or المضاعف) have the same letter for their second and third radicals. These two identical letters are written as one with a shaddah (ّ).",
        "In some conjugations, the two letters separate and each appears distinctly."
      ],
      "keyPoints": [
        "Root pattern: فَعَّ (where ع represents the doubled letter)",
        "Examples: مَدَّ (to extend), رَدَّ (to return), شَدَّ (to tighten)",
        "Past tense: مَدَّ، رَدَّ، ظَلَّ",
        "Present tense: يَمُدُّ، يَرُدُّ، يَشُدُّ",
        "Doubled letter separates in some forms: مَدَدْتُ (I extended)"
      ],
      "examples": [
        { "arabic": "مَدَّ يَدَهُ", "english": "He extended his hand" },
        { "arabic": "رَدَّ الْكِتَابَ", "english": "He returned the book" },
        { "arabic": "ظَلَّ فِي الْبَيْتِ", "english": "He stayed in the house" },
        { "arabic": "يَشُدُّ الْحَبْلَ", "english": "He tightens the rope" }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Conjugation Patterns",
      "titleArabic": "تصريف الفعل المضعف",
      "content": [
        "When a sukūn would appear on the first of the doubled letters, the letters separate."
      ],
      "keyPoints": [
        "Past with sukūn: مَدَدْتُ، مَدَدْتَ، مَدَدْنَا",
        "Jussive: لَمْ يَمْدُدْ (or لَمْ يَمُدَّ in some dialects)",
        "Imperative: مُدَّ (extend!), رُدَّ (return!)",
        "The shaddah indicates the two identical letters"
      ]
    }
  ],
